{"text": " I wish I knew sooner how insanely strong an airplane's wings are. What I'm about to show you cured my fear of flying. So a few months ago, I went on a zero gravity flight, which they do in a normal commercial plane. But to make you feel weightless in that plane, mid flight, the pilots have to go full thrust on the engines and pitch the plane into a sharp 47 degree incline along this path. And during this part, you feel squished to the floor, experiencing 1.8 Gs or hyper gravity. But the plane is also experiencing those forces. It's like putting the weight of a second plane onto the wings, which is surprisingly totally fine. An aircraft's wings are one of the strongest parts of a plane. They're mounted to the wing box, which is the primary low bearing structure of the wing. And attached to it are front and back wing spars that run the entire length and are supported by ribs in between. And this makes the wings not only strong, but flexible. During a normal commercial flight, the tips of this plane's wings might bend as much as two meters. But during the steepest parts of a zero G maneuver, the wing tips can flex as far as three meters. They actually test this on the ground, like this. And they don't break under five meters. And I've thought about that every single time I've been on a little bumpy flight since. So for more optimistic science and textories, follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 4.5600000000000005, "text": " I wish I knew sooner how insanely strong an airplane's wings are.", "tokens": [50364, 286, 3172, 286, 2586, 15324, 577, 40965, 2068, 364, 17130, 311, 11405, 366, 13, 50592], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1426057664174882, "compression_ratio": 1.6046511627906976, "no_speech_prob": 0.012667559087276459}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 4.5600000000000005, "end": 6.88, "text": " What I'm about to show you cured my fear of flying.", "tokens": [50592, 708, 286, 478, 466, 281, 855, 291, 29617, 452, 4240, 2